Zeitloser Klassiker.......





Gründer: Antoine LeCoultre





original Jaeger leCoultre Ref 252.8.71  Small Second mit Service Box.





Sehr geuter Zustand.


     





Gegründet: 1833





Manufacture Jaeger-LeCoultre SA, besser bekannt als Jaeger LeCoultre, ist ein Luxusuhrenhersteller mit Sitz in Le Sentier, Schweiz. Dieses Unternehmen ist eine hundertprozentige Tochtergesellschaft von Richemont, dem Schweizer Luxuskonzern, und das bereits seit dem Jahr 2000. Durch seine Erfindungen, Uhrwerke und Patente, die es in Hülle und Fülle gibt, ist Jaeger LeCoultre eine der Spitzenmarken von Richemont. und ein sehr angesehener Hersteller in der Uhrenbranche. Darüber hinaus sind viele namhafte Persönlichkeiten bekannt, die Armbanduhren von Jaeger LeCoultre tragen.





Eines der bekanntesten Stücke von Jaeger LeCoultre ist die Reverso. Der kurze und schlichte Name dieser Armbanduhr stammt von einer lateinischen Übersetzung und bedeutet „Ich drehe mich um“. Dieser Name ist passend, da sich das Gehäuse innerhalb seines Trägers drehen und drehen lässt. Diese Funktion schützt das Uhrglas und ermöglicht es der Reverso, den rauen und harten Schlägen eines Polospiels standzuhalten, wofür sie ursprünglich entwickelt und hergestellt wurde. Die Linie der Reverso-Uhren besteht aus mehreren Modellen, insbesondere der Reverso Classic Large Duoface Small Second, der Grande Reverso Ultra Thin Tribute und der Reverso Tribute Small Seconds Burgundy Red. Die Reverso wird bis heute hergestellt.

History of the luxury watch manufacturer Jaeger LeCoultre (source: Wikipedia):




Jaeger-LeCoultre


Jump to navigationJump to search


Jaeger-LeCoultre




Legal form joint stock company


Founded in 1833


Headquarters Le Sentier, Switzerland


Management Daniel Riedo


Number of employees approx. 1400


Sector Watch manufacture




Jaeger-LeCoultre (pronounced is a Swiss watch manufacturer that belongs to the Richemont Group and manufactures watches in the luxury price segment. The company is headquartered in Le Sentier, Switzerland, where it was first established in 1833 under the name LeCoultre.






History


19th century




Antoine LeCoultre (1803-1881). Picture around 1860




Registered share of 500 francs of sa de la Fabrique d'Horlogerie LeCoultre & Cie dated June 30, 1899.


Jacques David LeCoultre (1781-1850) and his son Charles Antoine LeCoultre (1803-1881) manufactured watch parts in Le Sentier and had made a name for themselves in improving the steel required for this purpose.[3] The LeCoultre company was founded in 1833 by Jacques LeCoultre's sons Charles Antoine and François Ulysse LeCoultre (1813-1895) in the Vallée de Joux, Canton Vaud. Eleven years later, Antoine LeCoultre, who had made a name for himself with the manufacture of high-quality pinions and the development of the "LeCoultre burin", invented a device for measuring micrometer distances, the millionometer. At the first World's Fair in London in 1851, he received a gold medal for his developments in the fields of precision and mechanization. In 1847, Antoine LeCoultre invented a keyless watch. It was equipped with a rocker operated by a small pusher, with the help of which it was possible to switch between winding and hand-setting functions. To avoid bankruptcy in 1858, a partner was sought and the company was renamed LeCoultre, Borgeaud & Cie. Fabrique d'horlogerie en blanc. By 1859, the company had about 100 employees.[4] Beginning in 1866, Antoine's son Élie LeCoultre modernized the company by introducing quality standards. By purchasing machinery and uniting all relevant trades under one roof, he created the first watch manufacture. This enabled the company to produce over 350 different movements from 1860 to 1890, 128 of which had chronograph functions and 99 of which had repeater mechanisms. In 1877, Antoine LeCoultre and Auguste Borgeaud handed over the business to LeCoultre's descendants. Under the management of the three sons, the company was renamed LeCoultre & Cie. In 1888, the company employed 480 people, half of whom worked at the company's premises in Le Sentier. In 1866, the LeCoultre & Cie company began making movements with small complications in small batches. Then in 1891, two complications, the chronograph function and the minute repeater, were combined in one movement. This development led to the production of large complications in the mid-1890s.




20th century


Jacques-David LeCoultre (1875-1948), the grandson of Antoine LeCoultre, became head of watchmaking in 1900 and general manager in 1906. From 1902, LeCoultre & Cie manufactured most of the raw movements (French: ébauches) of the Geneva-based watch brand Patek Philippe over a period of 30 years (in 1929, he had unsuccessfully sought a majority shareholding in Patek Philippe). From 1907, LeCoultre & Cie supplied raw movements to Edmond Jaeger (1850-1922), a Parisian watchmaker and industrialist from Alsace, based on Jaeger's designs for the world's flattest pocket watches (with caliber K145 having an overall height of 1.38 mm). In 1925, the caliber K7BF Duoplan was developed with the aim of improving the precision of movements for wristwatches. At that time, small wristwatches were in fashion. However, small movements often lacked reliability. Developed by Henri Rodanet, the technical director of Etablissements Ed. Jaeger, the movement of the Duoplan was arranged on two planes - hence the name of the model - and the winding crown was recessed into the case on the back. In this way, despite its small size, a large balance could be used to improve the watch's rate. In 1929, the Duoplan was the first wristwatch with sapphire crystal. In 1928, the skeletonized pocket watch Grande Complication Email Bleu (caliber 17JSSCCRVQ) with minute repeater, double-hand chronograph and perpetual calendar was produced.




In 1929, the development of the Duoplan led to the creation of what is still the world's smallest mechanical movement, the Caliber 101, whose original 74 (now 98) components together weighed about one gram. The second watch line equipped with the Caliber 101, the Joaillerie 101 Étrier, appeared in the 1930s. In 1953, Queen Elizabeth ii wore a Jaeger-LeCoultre 101 on her wrist at her coronation. Since 1931, the Reverso model has been offered with a reversible case, which was originally developed for polo players and in which the mineral crystal watch glass can be reversed to the back.




After Jacques-David LeCoultre joined forces with Edmond Jaeger, watchmaker to the French Navy and supplier to Cartier, in 1930, the Jaeger-LeCoultre company name was created.[5] The company's name is the Jaeger-LeCoultre.




The "atmospherically" driven Atmos table clock was developed in 1928 by Jean-Léon Reutter in Neuchâtel, who sold the patents to Edmond Jaeger in 1930. The first version, patented in 1928 and now known as Atmos 1, was marketed in 1930 by the Compagnie Générale de Radiologie (cgr). In 1936, LeCoultre first acquired the patents for France, and then for Switzerland in 1937. During the following decade, the company devoted itself to improving the mechanism before starting to manufacture them in their current form in 1946. In 2003, jlc launched the Atmos Mystérieuse, powered by the Jaeger-LeCoultre Caliber 583 and consisting of 1460 components. Since 2008, Jaeger-LeCoultre has commemorated the Austrian artist Gustav Klimt by dedicating the Atmos Marqueterie to him in an edition of ten, based on Klimt's work The Expectation.




LeCoultre & Cie's collaboration with Jaeger resulted in a merger of the two companies under the name Jaeger-LeCoultre in 1937 under Jacques-David LeCoultre. In 1938, under marketing director Georges Ketterer and administrative director Paul Lebet, the collaboration with Vacheron Constantin led to a union of the two companies in the holding company sapic.[6] One of Vacheron Constantin's directors, Henri Wallner, became managing director of sapic.[6] Another managing director of Vacheron Constantin, Charles Constantin, remained in his position. Since the Sentier workshops would henceforth supply the raw movements, Vacheron Constantin's raw movement developer, Albert Pellaton, left the company and joined iwc as technical director in 1944.[6] In 1944, the world's thinnest wristwatch movement at the time (caliber JLC903 or AP2003) was developed for Audemars Piguet, which was later also used by Vacheron Constantin (VC1003). Administrative director Paul Lebet died in 1945, and his position was transferred to Georges Ketterer.[6] Chairman of the board Jacques-David LeCoultre died in 1948, and he was also succeeded by Georges Ketterer.[6] Charles Constantin resigned in 1949 in favor of his nephew Léon Constantin.[6] With the death of Henri Wallner in 1951, all of Vacheron Constantin's former directors had thus left the management.




From 1950, the Memovox wristwatch was produced, as well as the Futurematic automatic watch from 1951, followed by the first self-winding wristwatch, the Memovox Automatic, from 1956. On the occasion of the International Geophysical Year in 1958, Jaeger-LeCoultre developed a watch that was less sensitive to magnetic fields and shocks and was water-resistant: the Geophysic chronometer watch, which Jules-César Savary proposed as a watch for research stations in Antarctica. It was powered by the K478BWS caliber, which featured seventeen jewels, a Breguet hairspring, a swan-neck spring on the balance cock, a shock protection system, and a Glucydur balance. In the year of its launch, the Geophysic was presented to William Anderson, the captain of the first American nuclear submarine to sail under the North Pole from the Pacific to the Atlantic. This was followed in 1959 by the first automatic wristwatch for divers, the Deep Sea Automatic Alarm.




In 1965, Georges Ketterer left sapic and Jaeger-LeCoultre as managing director and majority shareholder to head Vacheron Constantin, which had been spun off from sapic as a subsidiary at the same time.[6] Roger LeCoultre's remaining shares in sapic were transferred to a holding company called saphir. In 1967, jlc was involved with eleven other manufacturers in the development of the Beta 2, the first quartz wristwatch. in 1969, saphir was sold to Favre-Leuba, the world's oldest continuously producing watch manufacturer at the time. The management of saphir was subsequently taken over by Henry and Barbara Favre.




For the us market, due to tariff restrictions imposed by the Smoot-Hawley Tariff Act of 1930, the LeCoultre brand name was retained from the 1930s to the late 1970s. For the same reason, the watch cases, dials and hands of these watches were made in the usa. The distribution of the watches for the us market during this period was handled by the American company Vacheron-Constantin-LeCoultre, a subsidiary of Longines-Wittnauer. The Jaeger brand name, on the other hand, was used for watches produced in France.




Struck by the quartz crisis, a majority share of the company was sold to vdo Automotive in 1978. In 1982, the world's thinnest quartz movement was offered in the form of the K601 and, later that year, the K608. In 1986, vdo resold 40% of its shares to Audemars Piguet, but later acquired the remaining shares in Jaeger-LeCoultre, which were owned by the Ketterer family (25%) and a bank (20%). After the quartz crisis subsided, the first wristwatch with a perpetual calendar and automatic winding was produced in 1989, the Grand Réveil, and since 2004 the Master Grand Réveil (like previous ones, with an additional vibrating alarm).




21st century


In 2000, Mannesmann, which had acquired vdo in 1991, sold its stake in Jaeger-LeCoultre as part of Les Manufactures Horlogères, which held a 60% stake in Jaeger-LeCoultre and 100% stakes in each of iwc and a. Lange & Söhne, to the Swiss jewelry and luxury watch group Richemont. In the same year, Richemont bought the remaining 40% of jlc from Audemars Piguet. With more than 900 employees, Jaeger-LeCoultre had sales of more than 240 million Swiss francs in 2006. In 2006, jlc launched the Reverso grande complication à triptyque, the first watch with three dials whose displays are controlled by a single movement. In 2009, the Master Tourbillon and Reverso Gyrotourbillon 2 watches won the first two prizes in the international chronometry competition organized by the municipality of Le Locle and the LeLocle watch museum.[7]




Since 2004, the first wristwatch from Jaeger-LeCoultre with a large complication is the Gyrotourbillon i watch, with a gimbaled tourbillon. This was followed in 2009 by the Hybris Mechanica à Grande Sonnerie, consisting of 1300 individual parts with 26 complications, one of the most complicated wristwatches in the world. From 2010, the Master Grande Tradition Grande Complication was offered with an orbital tourbillon and minute repeater.

The Futurematic design legend by Jaeger LeCoultre (source: Wikipedia):








Futurematic E502 'Porthole'


The Futurematic is an automatic winding wristwatch model without a winding crown, which was manufactured by Jaeger-LeCoultre from 1951 to 1958.






Features


In 1951, the Futurematic was the world's first automatic watch without a winding crown. Characteristic of Futurematic watches is a flat crown on the case back, which is used only for setting the time.




The Futurematic watches were offered in two dial versions, both featuring a power reserve indicator and a seconds indicator in addition to hours and minutes in two smaller displays. The earlier version with the model name E501 has got watch hands in both small displays and was delivered with the calibers K497, K497/1 or KP827. The later version is called Futurematic Porthole (model designation E502), due to the two inset porthole-shaped small displays, and contains the calibers K817, K817/1 or K837. In the porthole of the seconds display, a disc with an arrow rotates, while in the porthole of the power reserve display, the color changes from red or blue (two variants) to white.




All calibers have a stop-second mechanism and a centrally suspended winding rotor that winds the barrel with an oscillation angle of 190 ° in both directions (pendulum winding). Furthermore, all Futurematic calibers feature an anti-magnetic balance that is twenty percent larger and heavier, a regulator with micrometer adjustment, and a unique hook mechanism (instead of the usual slipping clutch) to prevent excessive winding of the mainspring barrel. Complete relaxation of the mainspring in the barrel is avoided by design to allow the watch to restart immediately when put on. The latest calibers (KP827 and KP837) have a Parachoc shock protection, while the earlier calibers have a kif shock protection. The comparatively complex construction was the basis for the us advertising slogan of the Futurematic as "the world's most accurate automatic watch" at that time.[1] The Futurematic is the most accurate automatic watch in the world.




Due to the Smoot-Hawley Tariff Act, Futurematic models for the American market were printed and engraved with LeCoultre instead of Jaeger-LeCoultre. An exception to this is stainless steel case backs, which are always stamped with LeCoultre on the inside of both European and American watches during this period. The Swiss-made calibers for the American market were installed in watch cases produced in the usa. Distribution in North America was handled by Vacheron-Constantin-LeCoultre, a subsidiary of Longines-Wittnauer. Accordingly, the dials and case shapes used in the usa differed. For both models, the European versions had two case shapes (single-curve lugs or teardrop-shaped lugs) and in three materials (stainless steel, yellow gold, red gold), while in the usa, several shapes were produced in up to four materials (the previous three, plus 10-carat rolled gold-plated).




History of the military/luxury watch manufacture Jaeger Lecoultre (source: Wikipedia):




Jacques David LeCoultre (1781-1850) and his son Charles Antoine LeCoultre (1803-1881) manufactured watch parts in Le Sentier and had made a name for themselves in improving the steel required for this purpose.[2] The LeCoultre company was founded in 1833 by Jacques LeCoultre's sons Charles Antoine and François Ulysse LeCoultre (1813-1895) in the Vallée de Joux, Canton Vaud. Eleven years later, Antoine LeCoultre, who had made a name for himself with the manufacture of high-quality pinions and the development of the "LeCoultre burin", invented a device for measuring micrometer distances, the millionometer. At the first World's Fair in London in 1851, he received a gold medal for his developments in the fields of precision and mechanization. In 1847, Antoine LeCoultre invented a keyless watch. It was equipped with a rocker operated by a small pusher, with the help of which it was possible to switch between winding and hand-setting functions. To avoid bankruptcy in 1858, a partner was sought and the company was renamed LeCoultre, Borgeaud & Cie. Fabrique d'horlogerie en blanc. By 1859, the company had about 100 employees.[3] Beginning in 1866, Antoine's son Élie LeCoultre modernized the company by introducing quality standards. By purchasing machinery and uniting all relevant trades under one roof, he created the first watch manufacture. This enabled the company to produce over 350 different movements from 1860 to 1890, 128 of which had chronograph functions and 99 of which had repeater mechanisms. In 1877, Antoine LeCoultre and Auguste Borgeaud handed over the business to LeCoultre's descendants. Under the management of the three sons, the company was renamed LeCoultre & Cie. In 1888, the company employed 480 people, half of whom worked at the company's premises in Le Sentier. In 1866, the LeCoultre & Cie company began making movements with small complications in small batches. Then in 1891, two complications, the chronograph function and the minute repeater, were combined in one movement. This development led to the production of large complications in the mid-1890s.




20th century


Jacques-David LeCoultre (1875-1948), the grandson of Antoine LeCoultre, became head of watchmaking in 1900 and general manager in 1906. From 1902, LeCoultre & Cie manufactured most of the raw movements (French ébauches) of the Geneva-based watch brand Patek Philippe over a period of 30 years (in 1929, it had unsuccessfully sought the sharemehr in Patek Philippe). From 1907, LeCoultre & Cie supplied raw movements to Edmond Jaeger (1850-1922), a Parisian watchmaker and industrialist from Alsace, based on Jaeger's designs for the world's thinnest pocket watches (with caliber K145 having a height of 1.38 mm). In 1925, the caliber K7BF Duoplan was developed with the aim of improving the precision of movements for wristwatches. At that time, small wristwatches were in fashion. However, small movements often lacked reliability. Developed by Henri Rodanet, the technical director of the Etablissements Ed. Jaeger, the movement of the Duoplan was arranged on two levels - hence the name of the model - and the winding crown was recessed into the case on the back. In this way, despite its small size, a large balance could be used to improve the watch's rate. In 1929, the Duoplan was the first wristwatch with sapphire crystal. In 1928, the skeletonized pocket watch Grande Complication Email Bleu (caliber 17JSSCCRVQ) with minute repeater, double-hand chronograph and perpetual calendar was produced.




In 1929, the development of the Duoplan led to the creation of what is still the world's smallest mechanical movement, the Caliber 101, whose original 74 (now 98) components together weighed about one gram. The second watch line equipped with the Caliber 101, the Joaillerie 101 Étrier, appeared in the 1930s. In 1953, Queen Elizabeth ii wore a Jaeger-LeCoultre 101 on her wrist at her coronation. Since 1931, the Reverso model has been offered with a reversible case, which was originally developed for polo players and in which the mineral crystal watch glass can be reversed to the back.




After Jacques-David LeCoultre joined forces with Edmond Jaeger, watchmaker to the French Navy and supplier to Cartier, in 1930, the Jaeger-LeCoultre company name was created.[4] The company's name was the same as that of Cartier.




The Atmos atmospherically driven table clock was developed in 1928 by Jean-Léon Reutter in Neuchâtel, who sold the patents to Edmond Jaeger in 1930. The first version, patented in 1928 and now known as Atmos 1, was marketed in 1930 by the Compagnie Générale de Radiologie (cgr). In 1936, LeCoultre first acquired the patents for France, and then for Switzerland in 1937. During the following decade, the company devoted itself to improving the mechanism before starting to manufacture them in their current form in 1946. In 2003, jlc launched the Atmos Mystérieuse, powered by the Jaeger-LeCoultre Caliber 583 and consisting of 1460 components. Since 2008, Jaeger-LeCoultre has commemorated the Austrian artist Gustav Klimt by dedicating the Atmos Marqueterie to him in an edition of ten, based on Klimt's work The Expectation.




LeCoultre & Cie's collaboration with Jaeger resulted in a merger of the two companies under the name Jaeger-LeCoultre in 1937 under Jacques-David LeCoultre. In 1938, under marketing director Georges Ketterer and administrative director Paul Lebet, the collaboration with Vacheron Constantin led to a union of the two companies in the holding company sapic.[5] One of Vacheron Constantin's directors, Henri Wallner, became an executive director of sapic.[5] Another executive director of Vacheron Constantin, Charles Constantin, remained in his position. Since the supply of raw movements would henceforth be handled by the Sentier workshops, Vacheron Constantin's raw movement developer, Albert Pellaton, left the company and joined iwc as technical director in 1944.[5] In 1944, the world's thinnest wristwatch movement at the time (caliber JLC903 or AP2003) was developed for Audemars Piguet, which was later also used by Vacheron Constantin (VC1003). Administrative director Paul Lebet died in 1945, and his position was transferred to Georges Ketterer.[5] Chairman of the board Jacques-David LeCoultre died in 1948, and he was also succeeded by Georges Ketterer.[5] Charles Constantin resigned in 1949 in favor of his nephew Léon Constantin.[5] With the death of Henri Wallner in 1951, all of Vacheron Constantin's former directors had thus left the management.




From 1950, the Memovox wristwatch was produced, as well as the Futurematic automatic watch from 1951, followed by the first self-winding wristwatch, the Memovox Automatic, from 1956. On the occasion of the International Geophysical Year in 1958, Jaeger-LeCoultre developed a watch that was less sensitive to magnetic fields and shocks and was water-resistant: the Geophysic chronometer watch, which Jules-César Savary proposed as a watch for research stations in Antarctica. It was powered by the K478BWS caliber, which featured seventeen jewels, a Breguet hairspring, a swan-neck spring on the balance cock, a shock protection system, and a Glucydur balance. In the year of its launch, the Geophysic was presented to William Anderson, the captain of the first American nuclear submarine to sail under the North Pole from the Pacific to the Atlantic. In 1959, the first automatic wristwatch for divers, the Deep Sea Automatic Alarm, followed.




In 1965, Georges Ketterer left sapic and Jaeger-LeCoultre as managing director and majority shareholder to head Vacheron Constantin, which had been spun off from sapic as a subsidiary at the same time.[5] Roger LeCoultre's remaining shares in sapic were transferred to a holding company called saphir. In 1967, jlc was involved with eleven other manufacturers in the development of the Beta 2, the first quartz wristwatch. in 1969, saphir was sold to Favre-Leuba, the world's oldest continuously producing watch manufacturer at the time. The management of saphir was subsequently taken over by Henry and Barbara Favre.




For the us market, due to tariff restrictions imposed by the Smoot-Hawley Tariff Act of 1930, the LeCoultre brand name was retained from the 1930s to the late 1970s. For the same reason, the watch cases, dials and hands of these watches were manufactured in the usa. The distribution of the watches for the us market during this period was handled by the American company Vacheron-Constantin-LeCoultre, a subsidiary of Longines-Wittnauer. The Jaeger brand name, on the other hand, was used for watches produced in France.




Struck by the quartz crisis, a majority share of the company was sold to vdo Automotive in 1978. In 1982, the world's thinnest quartz movement was offered in the form of the K601 and, later that year, the K608. In 1986, vdo resold 40% of its shares to Audemars Piguet, but later acquired the remaining shares in Jaeger-LeCoultre, which were owned by the Ketterer family (25%) and a bank (20%). After the quartz crisis subsided, the first wristwatch with a perpetual calendar and automatic winding was produced in 1989, the Grand Réveil, and since 2004 the Master Grand Réveil (like previous ones, with an additional vibrating alarm).

In 2003, jlc launched the Atmos Mystérieuse, powered by the Jaeger-LeCoultre Caliber 583 and consisting of 1460 components. Since 2008, Jaeger-LeCoultre has commemorated the Austrian artist Gustav Klimt by dedicating the Atmos Marqueterie to him in an edition of ten, based on Klimt's work The Expectation.




LeCoultre & Cie's collaboration with Jaeger resulted in a merger of the two companies under the name Jaeger-LeCoultre in 1937 under Jacques-David LeCoultre. In 1938, under marketing director Georges Ketterer and administrative director Paul Lebet, the collaboration with Vacheron Constantin led to a union of the two companies in the holding company sapic.[5] One of Vacheron Constantin's directors, Henri Wallner, became an executive director of sapic.[5] Another executive director of Vacheron Constantin, Charles Constantin, remained in his position. Since the supply of raw movements would henceforth be handled by the Sentier workshops, Vacheron Constantin's raw movement developer, Albert Pellaton, left the company and joined iwc as technical director in 1944.[5] In 1944, the world's thinnest wristwatch movement at the time (caliber JLC903 or AP2003) was developed for Audemars Piguet, which was later also used by Vacheron Constantin (VC1003). Administrative director Paul Lebet died in 1945, and his position was transferred to Georges Ketterer.[5] Chairman of the board Jacques-David LeCoultre died in 1948, and he was also succeeded by Georges Ketterer.[5] Charles Constantin resigned in 1949 in favor of his nephew Léon Constantin.[5] With the death of Henri Wallner in 1951, all of Vacheron Constantin's former directors had thus left the management.




From 1950, the Memovox wristwatch was produced, as well as the Futurematic automatic watch from 1951, followed by the first self-winding wristwatch, the Memovox Automatic, from 1956. On the occasion of the International Geophysical Year in 1958, Jaeger-LeCoultre developed a watch that was less sensitive to magnetic fields and shocks and was water-resistant: the Geophysic chronometer watch, which Jules-César Savary proposed as a watch for research stations in Antarctica. It was powered by the K478BWS caliber, which featured seventeen jewels, a Breguet hairspring, a swan-neck spring on the balance cock, a shock protection system, and a Glucydur balance. In the year of its launch, the Geophysic was presented to William Anderson, the captain of the first American nuclear submarine to sail under the North Pole from the Pacific to the Atlantic. In 1959, the first automatic wristwatch for divers, the Deep Sea Automatic Alarm, followed.




In 1965, Georges Ketterer left sapic and Jaeger-LeCoultre as managing director and majority shareholder to head Vacheron Constantin, which had been spun off from sapic as a subsidiary at the same time.[5] Roger LeCoultre's remaining shares in sapic were transferred to a holding company called saphir. In 1967, jlc was involved with eleven other manufacturers in the development of the Beta 2, the first quartz wristwatch. in 1969, saphir was sold to Favre-Leuba, the world's oldest continuously producing watch manufacturer at the time. The management of saphir was subsequently taken over by Henry and Barbara Favre.




For the us market, due to tariff restrictions imposed by the Smoot-Hawley Tariff Act of 1930, the LeCoultre brand name was retained from the 1930s to the late 1970s. For the same reason, the watch cases, dials and hands of these watches were manufactured in the usa. The distribution of the watches for the us market during this period was handled by the American company Vacheron-Constantin-LeCoultre, a subsidiary of Longines-Wittnauer. The Jaeger brand name, on the other hand, was used for watches produced in France.




Struck by the quartz crisis, a majority share of the company was sold to vdo Automotive in 1978. In 1982, the world's thinnest quartz movement was offered in the form of the K601 and, later that year, the K608. In 1986, vdo resold 40% of its shares to Audemars Piguet, but later acquired the remaining shares in Jaeger-LeCoultre, which were owned by the Ketterer family (25%) and a bank (20%). After the quartz crisis subsided, the first wristwatch with perpetual calendar and automatic winding was produced in 1989, the Grand Réveil, and since 2004 the Master Grand Réveil (like previous ones, with additional vibrating alarm).

size:
"Reverso" is famous for being able to flip the face from the front to the back. Since its introduction in 1931, it has been loved by many watch fans as a representative model of Jaeger Lecoultre. Originally, this face-reversing case was created to prevent the glass from breaking during polo competitions. Today, however, the flipped reverse side is used for "engraving space", "space for showing the movement", "space for adding functions", etc., creating a variety of attractive Reversos.

The belt is non-genuine. There are some small scratches, but it is in a beautiful state. We are doing overhaul and exterior finishing.

Case diameter about: 20.5x33mm

name:

size:
"Reverso" is famous for being able to flip the face from the front to the back. Since its introduction in 1931, it has been loved by many watch fans as a representative model of Jaeger Lecoultre. Among them, this is a model that appeared as a limited edition of 500 in 2003. It is the second version of the Reverso made with a platinum case and the second version of the Reverso Tourbillon. The dial is simply a second hand and a power reserve indicator, but you can admire the tourbillon carriage from the back. At the time of its release, it is a rare model that was said to be about 20 pieces in stock in Japan.

The belt is non-genuine. There is discoloration on the dial, and there are some other small scratches, but it is in a beautiful state. With box (the outer box is dirty), no warranty card. Simple adjustments and exterior finishing are performed.

Case diameter approx. 26mm x 42mm (including lugs)

"Reverso" is famous for being able to flip the face from the front to the back. Since its introduction in 1931, it has been loved by many watch fans as a representative model of Jaeger Lecoultre. JLC Q178T470 Tactical BlaBucklested Case and 



Pre-Owned Jaeger-LeCoultre Master Compressor Diver GMT Navy Seals (Q178T470) self-winding automatic watch, features a 46mm titanium case surrounding a black dial on a black leather strap with a titanium tang buckle. Functions include hours, minutes, seconds, date, GMT and chronograph. 



Description


Jaeger LeCoultre Master Compressor Men's watch. Limited of 1500 Navy Seals edition. Titanium case with a black leather strap. Uni-directional rotating ceramic bezel. Black dial with luminous hands and stick hour markers. Arabic numeral marks the 12 o'clock position. Minute markers around the outer rim. Dial Type: Analog. Luminescent hands and markers. Date display between 4 and 5 o'clock positions. Chronograph - three sub-dials displaying: 60 second, 30 minute and 12 hour. Automatic movement. Calibre 757 engine. Scratch resistant sapphire crystal. Solid case back. Case diameter: 46 mm. Round case shape. Tang clasp. Water resistant at 300 meters/ 1000 feet. Functions: chronograph, date, hour, minute, second. Luxury watch style. Watch label: Swiss Made. Jaeger LeCoultre Master Compressor Chronograph Titanium Men's Watch Q178T471

size:
"Reverso" is famous for being able to flip the face from the front to the back. Since its introduction in 1931, it has been loved by many watch fans as a representative model of Jaeger Lecoultre. Originally, this face-reversing case was created to prevent the glass from breaking during polo competitions. Today, however, the flipped reverse side is used for "engraving space", "space for showing the movement", "space for adding functions", etc., creating a variety of attractive Reversos. This is a gorgeous model with diamonds set on the top and bottom of the case.

There are some small scratches, but it is in a beautiful state. With box and warranty. I am replacing the battery.

Case diameter approx. 19.5mm x 40mm (including lugs)
